          "body": "Judges 4 opens with the most compressed form of the book's theological framework. Three verses narrate a twenty-year arc: Israel does evil (4:1), the LORD sells them into Canaanite bondage (4:2), and Israel cries to the LORD under the weight of nine hundred iron chariots (4:3). The cycle is not presented as tragedy but as pedagogy — the oppression is the LORD's instrument of discipline, and the cry is the beginning of restoration. The verb 'sold' (*makhar*, 4:2) is striking: God acts as a sovereign disposing of what belongs to Him in response to covenant breach. The same verb will reappear in 4:9 when the LORD 'sells' Sisera into the hand of a woman — the word of divine judicial commerce runs in both directions. What God uses as discipline He can also use as deliverance."
