          "body": "The battle itself occupies only two verses (4:14-15), and the brevity is deliberate. Everything the narrative has built — Sisera's nine hundred iron chariots (named three times: 4:3, 7, 13), the twenty years of oppression, the gathering of ten thousand men — is resolved by a single statement: 'The LORD routed Sisera and all his chariots and all his army with the edge of the sword before Barak' (4:15). The LORD is the grammatical subject; Barak is the beneficiary. Chapter 5's poetic version of the same battle (5:20-21) adds that the stars fought from heaven and the River Kishon swept the enemy away — divine intervention through natural forces that turned the chariot-favorable plain into a chariot trap. When God goes before His people (4:14, 'the LORD has gone out before you'), the technology the enemy trusted becomes their liability. Sisera's chariots, which made him formidable on dry ground, became useless and then lethal as the Kishon flooded. He abandons the chariot that had been his power and flees on foot (4:15) — the chapter's first image of reversal. Charles Spurgeon, preaching on the judges, noted that God habitually strips His enemies of their strongest weapon at the moment of His choosing; the enemy's pride in his nine hundred chariots was precisely what made their rout so complete."
